#Mean ratings for gain manipulation check by group

Column graph:

yup except when you want to match to 1 thing, you use == rather than %in%. If you want to match to any of the items in a list, use %in% c(“thingone”, “thingtwo”). The group_by here isn’t necessary either. You only need that when you want to do a summarise right after.

gainmanip <- manipcheck %>%
  filter(question == "gainmanipulation") 

gainmanip %>%
    ggplot(aes(x = group, y = mean, fill = group)) +
    geom_col(width = 0.5, show.legend = FALSE) +
    scale_y_continuous(expand = c(0,0),
                       limits = c(0,5)) +
    geom_errorbar(aes(ymin=mean-StdErr, ymax=mean+StdErr),
                  size=.3, 
                  width=.2) +
  theme_classic() +
  labs(title = "To what extent did the information stress the positive benefits of \nadopting open science practices?", x="Condition", y="Mean ratings of gain manipulation")

glimpse(manipcheck)
## Rows: 4
## Columns: 6
## $ group    <chr> "gain", "gain", "loss", "loss"
## $ question <chr> "negative_conseq", "positive_benefits", "negative_conseq", "p…
## $ mean     <dbl> 3.320000, 4.243710, 3.622429, 4.137467
## $ SD       <dbl> 1.1916419, 0.6131329, 1.2204697, 0.8553616
## $ N        <dbl> 65, 65, 80, 80
## $ StdErr   <dbl> 0.14780499, 0.07604977, 0.13645266, 0.09563234
  manipcheck$group[manipcheck$group == "gain"] <- "Gain"
  manipcheck$group[manipcheck$group == "loss"] <- "Loss"
  manipcheck$question[manipcheck$question == "gainmanipulation"] <- "Gain-Framed Manipulation"
  manipcheck$question[manipcheck$question == "lossmanipulation"] <- "Loss-Framed Manipulation"

manipcheck %>%
    ggplot(aes(x = group, y = mean, fill = group)) +
    geom_col(width = 0.7, position = "dodge", show.legend = FALSE) +
    scale_y_continuous(expand = c(0,0),
                       limits = c(0,5)) +
    theme_classic() +
    facet_wrap(~ question) +
    geom_errorbar(aes(ymin=mean-StdErr, ymax=mean+StdErr),
                  size=.3,
                  width=.2,
                  position=position_dodge(.9)) +
     labs(x="Condition", y="Mean ratings of information")

JR yes you want to check what kind of data R thinks each variable is using glimpse(). It is showing both group and question as characters, rather htan factors. You can use the same kind of code you were using above to convert 1 and 2 to gain loss to change the labels of both. Dont forget to use the <- to assign the output to the df, so that it sticks around.

clean_data <- clean_data %>% mutate(group = factor(group, # levels = c(1, 2), #labels = c(“Gain”, “Loss”)))

  per_att_int$group[per_att_int$group == "gain"] <- "Gain"
  per_att_int$group[per_att_int$group == "loss"] <- "Loss"
  per_att_int$question[per_att_int$question == "perception"] <- "Perception"
  per_att_int$question[per_att_int$question == "attitude"] <- "Attitude"
  per_att_int$question[per_att_int$question == "intention"] <- "Intention"

per_att_int_ordered <- per_att_int
per_att_int_ordered$question <- factor(per_att_int_ordered$question,
                         levels = c("Perception", "Attitude", "Intention"))

per_att_int_ordered %>%
    ggplot(aes(x = group, y = mean, fill = group)) +
    geom_col(width = 0.7, position = "dodge", show.legend = FALSE) +
    scale_y_continuous(expand = c(0,0),
                       limits = c(0,5)) +
    theme_classic() +
    facet_wrap(~ question) +
    geom_errorbar(aes(ymin=mean-StdErr, ymax=mean+StdErr),
                  size=.3,
                  width=.2,
                  position=position_dodge(.9)) +
     labs(x="Condition", y="Mean ratings")
